<div id="comment_status_64472469" class="commentstatus"></div>
<div id="comment_64472469" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_64472469" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a id="comment_link_64472469" name="comment_link_64472469" href="//tech.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23323011&amp;cid=64472469" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64472469)" >Re:</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64472469" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64472469); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>3</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~Tailhook">Tailhook</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~Tailhook">( 98486 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64472469"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64472469"><p><div class="quote"><p>Since one can migrate a VMWare VM to KVM, why use VMWare on Linux?</p></div><p>There aren't really many good reasons to use VMWare on Linux any longer.  There used to be: VMWare, at one time, was far easier to deal with.  Today, the KVM/QEMU stack is pretty friendly.  It still isn't as polished as VMWare's nice UI, etc., but it's entirely tolerable, and much, much lighter weight.  Where things get interesting is around sophisticated stuff like live migration, PCI passthrough, GPUs, etc.  In some areas KVM is ahead of VMWare, in others VMWare is superior.

</p><p>Mainly, the appeal of VMWare<span class="substr"> </span></p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64472469">

</div>
</div>

